.SH "Device Options (1-wire Bus Master)"
These options give the location of the 1-wire adapter that connects the program to the actual 1-wire bus and the
.I iButtons
or 1-wire devices on it. The bus master is either an actual physical device, or an 
.B owserver (1). 
.P
At least one device option is required. There is no default. More than one device can be listed, and all will be used. (A logical union unless you explore the \fI/bus.n/\fR directories.)
.SH "* Serial devices"
.I port 
specifies a serial port, e.g. 
.I /dev/ttyS0
.TP
\fI-d port\fI \fR|\fR \fI--device=port\fI
DS2480B-based bus master (like the DS9097U or the LINK in emulation mode). If the adapter doesn't respond, a passive type (diode/resistor) circuit will be assumed.
.TP
\fI--link=port\fI
.B iButtonLink
.I LINK
adapter (all versions) in non-emulation mode. Uses an ascii protocol over serial.
.TP
\fI--passive=port\fR | \fI--ha3=port\fR | \fI--ha4b=port
Passive 1-wire adapters.
.SH "* USB devices"
Multiple USB devices can be perplexing since the order of devices is not predictable. 
.I ALL
will use all the available USB adapters.
.TP
.I -u  \fR|\ \fI--usb\fR[\fI=ALL\fR]
DS2490 based bus master (like the DS9490R).
.SH "* I2C devices"
I2C is  2 wire protocol used for chip-to-chip communication. The busmasters:
.I DS2482-100, DS2482-101
and
.I DS2482-800
can specify (via pin voltages) a subset of addresses on the i2c bus. Those choices are
.P
.I i2c_address
.TP
0,1,2,3
0x18,0x19,0x1A,0x1B
.TP
4,5,6,7
0x1C,0x1D,0x1E,0x1F (DS2482-800 only)
.P
.I port
for i2c masters have the form 
.I /dev/i2c-0, /dev/i2c-1, ...
.TP
\fI-d port\fR | \fI--device=port
This form only permits a specific 
.I port 
and the first available
.I i2c_address
.TP
\fI--i2c=port\fR | \fI--i2c=port:i2c_address\fR | \fI--i2c=port:ALL
Specific i2c
.I port
and the
.I i2c_address
is either the first, specific, or all or them. The 
.I i2c_address
is 0,1,2,...
.TP
\fI--i2c\fR | \fI--i2c=:\fR | \fI--i2c=ALL:ALL
Search the available i2c buses for either the first, the first, or every i2c adapter.
.SH "* Network devices"
These bus masters communicate via the tcp/ip network protocol. 
The
.I network_address
is of the form tcp_address:port
.P
E.g. 192.168.0.1:3000 or localhost:3000
.TP
.I --link=network_address
LinkHubE network LINK adapter
.TP
.I --ha7net=network_address
HA7Net network 1-wire adapter
.TP
.I --etherweather=network_address
Etherweather adapter
.TP
\fI-s network_address\fR | \fI--server=network_address
Location of an
.B owserver (1)
program that talks to the 1-wire bus. The default port of 4304 will be used by default.
.SH "* Simulated devices"
Used for testing and development. 
.I chips
is a list of comma-separated family codes. e.g. 10,21,1B
.TP
.I --fake=chips
Random address and random values for each read.
.TP
.I --tester=chips
Predicable address and predictable values for each read. (See the website for the algorhythm).